Price / FAAMG Ratio
Instead of Price/Sales or Price/Earnings, high-potential tech companies are=
 subconsciously being valued on Price / FAAMG, or a probability that those =
companies will become as big as today=E2=80=99s biggest, and it=E2=80=99s n=
ot crazy.
(If I=E2=80=99m wrong, and we actually are in a bubble that=E2=80=99s about=
 to pop, this is the statement that=E2=80=99s going to get me roasted.)
Let me explain. Traditionally, companies are valued based on a multiple of =
their earnings or profits per share (Price/Earnings or P/E), or if they=E2=
=80=99re earlier in their journey and growing fast but still unprofitable, =
on a multiple of their revenue (Price / Sales or P/S), or a free cash flow =
multiple, or some other financial metric.=20
But today, in both private and public markets, with P/E and P/S ratios at u=
selessly high levels, it seems like companies are being valued on a rough p=
robability that they can become as big as the biggest companies, which are =
themselves more valuable than ever before. With the $1 trillion barrier bro=
ken, and $2 trillion taken down within a year, there=E2=80=99s no more psyc=
hological ceiling. That=E2=80=99s where the seemingly crazy prices are comi=
ng from.
Now of course, this kind of valuation takes a healthy dose of optimism, and=
 this market is ripe for dreaming, for reasons we=E2=80=99ve covered before=
:=C2=A0
Tech Strength. Tech companies are actually benefiting from COVID as more ac=
tivity and commerce moves online.=C2=A0
More Cash and Envy. US personal savings rates doubled, from 7.3% to 14.1%, =
over the past year. People are seeing their friends get rich and want to pu=
t their savings to work.
The Fed. The Fed is printing money, and providing a backstop that makes ris=
ky assets less risky.=C2=A0
Rates are at all-time lows. That means money is cheap and investors are tur=
ning to equities (and alternative assets, including venture) for yield. It =
also means that=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Discount Rates are low. Discount rates are how investors figure out what fu=
ture cash flows are worth today. We=E2=80=99re not there, but for illustrat=
ive purposes, a discount rate of 0% would mean that an investor values $1 b=
illion generated in 2031 as much as $1 billion generated today.=C2=A0
In a structurally risk-on environment, people aren=E2=80=99t looking for re=
asons not to invest, they=E2=80=99re looking for justifications to invest. =
They want to put their money to work and they don=E2=80=99t want to miss ou=
t on the next $100 billion, $1 trillion, or even $2 trillion company.=20
I don=E2=80=99t think they=E2=80=99re wrong to think that way. In fact, rel=
ative to the biggest tech companies, the best startups and smaller cap tech=
 companies are still undervalued compared to a decade ago.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s my logic: FAAMG stocks seem to be reasonably priced and good=
 anchors off of which everything else is pegged. FAAMG (particularly Amazon=
 and FB) market caps have actually grown faster than startup and non-FAAMG =
public tech valuations. Startup and non-FAAMG valuation growth is just star=
ting to catch up to FAAMG growth over the past year.=C2=A0
Startups and smaller cap tech companies are being valued based on a probabi=
lity that they can become as big as the FAAMG companies (or the biggest com=
panies in their verticals), and even at the same probability, they should b=
e worth 5-15x as much as they were worth a decade ago, because the ceiling =
has risen that much.
In other words, if you think that FAAMG are reasonably valued, and you thin=
k that the probability of newer companies coming in and eventually growing =
as big as the biggest tech companies is about the same as it was a decade a=
go, startups and smaller cap tech companies are actually fairly valued or e=
ven undervalued today.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
