rn, impacts the ceiling of API-first and fintech companies at earlier stage=
s.
Stripe is rumored to have raised at a $100 billion valuation recently, and =
rumors of secondary market transactions in the $125 - $150 billion price ra=
nge abound. Most people I=E2=80=99ve spoken to about it don=E2=80=99t know =
what Stripe=E2=80=99s numbers look like; instead, they=E2=80=99re saying th=
ings like, =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a very good chance this is a $1 trillio=
n+ company, the next FAAMG, so even if $150 billion feels expensive today, =
this could 8-15x.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Stripe is kind of in a league of its own, without a perfect comp among FAAM=
G. But it has that =E2=80=9Cthis could become the biggest company in the wo=
rld=E2=80=9D mystique around it. The biggest company in the world, today, i=
s Apple at $2.27 trillion. That=E2=80=99s a high ceiling.=C2=A0
Even if it=E2=80=99s just Visa, with its $448 billion market cap, that=E2=
=80=99s a 3x.=C2=A0
With Stripe as an anchor, API-first startups are raising at big valuations.=
 In November 2020, Checkr [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuhDAM_Jr=
NEeXlJRxy6KW_gRLHQLSQoBBa8ffNLodKI1uWNR7PoKs053LZPR-VvctYr51sot9jpVqpsPOgMs=
ZgxVMaBXpgweogDBgWj3EqRJuLq63lJLaffo3oaszpw-BcAlvss38G7gfRw6S4UR4Rez0QmB74p=
BFvXXeGSAnJ0g-VKydiq11q3Y-H-nrI7wZcCF-lw7y1gUUruRQNIBS02onOaPBIPCiYgEstlTeo=
Aml0BH7i5qH5NsvuOP1RHb7el1ixKVefS0xzW78Wt9H6WTQzY-vbmWK9RkrOrxRun_WO6-N8nCl=
RaTGG0dUWklBq6IUajIDbVwtCSWjPAGdNOeTGSv-ifxV-gEo], which is an API-first ba=
ckground check company, raised at a $2.2 billion post-money valuation. In J=
anuary, Check [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuxCAM_JrlGPHyhhw49NL=
fQDycBG0CKZBW-fvSzaHSyJZljccz3jZccrn0kWsjf8W060Cd8Kdu2BoWclYsJgbNnlwJkBMJWg=
amQJFYzVwQdxs33cqJ5DjdFr1tMac3g1IOZNUepie1ME9AJSigbHQMxwDUc5hHeN669gwRk0eN3=
1iunJBsem3tqA_x8eCfHX5F_1q_Bp_3PpGoOeWsA5iAXgc2KAnOIw0CZqBccuGUFwGltwhupuoh=
6b7woZ6uNutff5dI0Sk3l0tMS1-_Vrvj9l50N6b3_UyxXQaTdRuG22i783pbNwsmLD3HYGzrKTE=
hppGJSTG4jfUkBIf-DFDSlUPurPQv-gsKuYAa], which is building a payroll-as-a-se=
rvice API, just came out of stealth and raised a $35 million Series B [http=
s://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuhDAMhk8z2RXlQZiwyKKbXgMljoFoIKHBtOL2zc=
CikmXL8uO3P3CEUy6n3fJO7O0GOje0CX_3BYmwsGPHMsRgRSeN0m3Pgm2DMNqwuA9jQVxdXCyVA=
9l2-CWCo5jTNcG51Gy2ZnQOnO60xIBgeGfgyeUzhF4AON7euu4IEROgxR8sZ07IFjsTbftDfT7k=
VzWYEV7zdwN5rZlf8lRDTFRyOCCm6eNqYNFKLkU1LZSuvhGNabUH5EHpUXPZSuUNqIAtONR-5Ob=
R8nWSzX74nRy83gqs2JTJ51IX1_JrdisuV6F-OdS4HinSOWByfsFwA6Cb44VkmDBhqXzD4KjSE0=
r1T6F6I_T9cCWkpK7HaM6qcsh1Kv2L_gHp2Ypw] (led by Stripe and Thrive), which l=
ikely values it somewhere near $300 million post-money.=20
Those feel high for their rounds, but translate to a 1-in-45 chance that Ch=
eckr achieves what Stripe has to-date, and a 1-in-8 chance Check achieves w=
hat Checkr has, with some slight discount for time. Those seem like reasona=
ble bets to make given that they=E2=80=99re two massive, perfect API-first =
use cases, of which there aren=E2=80=99t many, run by strong, experienced t=
eams with great early traction. I=E2=80=99d rather invest in Checkr and Che=
ck than ten =E2=80=9Ccheaper=E2=80=9D but worse API-first companies =E2=80=
=94 you get what you pay for.
Shopify and Amazon
Shopify=E2=80=99s relationship with Amazon is the textbook example of P/FAA=
MG valuation.=C2=A0
Since going public in May 2015, Shopify=E2=80=99s stock is up over 5,000%. =
It=E2=80=99s currently trading at a 60x NTM EV / Revenue multiple and a 395=
=2E7x NTM PE ratio. Those are both very=20=
high numbers if you=E2=80=99re valuin=
g Shopify based on the fundamentals, and indeed, Shopify has felt expensive=
 at almost every point on its meteoric rise since late 2018. I made this ch=
art back in May to describe what it=E2=80=99s felt like thinking about inve=
sting in SHOP:=C2=A0
Since then, it=E2=80=99s up another 90%. Crazy, right? But what if you look=
 at SHOP=E2=80=99s valuation as a probability that it will become as big as=
 Amazon?
Breaking apart SHOP=E2=80=99s valuation that way, there are two factors: ho=
w much has Amazon grown, and how much has the probability that Shopify beco=
mes as big as Amazon changed?=C2=A0
Amazon Market Cap. Over the past five years, Amazon has grown its market ca=
p 6.7x, from $245 billion to $1.65 trillion.=C2=A0
Probability SHOP Becomes AMZN. The implied probability that Shopify becomes=
 Amazon, based on their relative market caps, has increased from 0.68% to 1=
0.76%, not taking into account the fact that Amazon is likely to continue t=
o get bigger as SHOP catches up.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s assume Amazon=E2=80=99s future growth and the discount rate c=
ome out in the wash, which is conservative, and we=E2=80=99re left with an =
~11% chance that Shopify becomes as big as Amazon. If you believe that Amaz=
on is fairly valued, and that an 11% chance of Shopify becoming Amazon is r=
easonable, then Shopify=E2=80=99s market cap isn=E2=80=99t as crazy as it s=
eems from looking only at traditional valuation metrics.
Onwards and Upwards
There=E2=80=99s a trope going around that since companies are raising more,=
 earlier, at higher valuations, investors need to sit out or sacrifice retu=
rns by ignoring price to get into the hottest deals. After digging into the=
 numbers, I just don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s true. The ceiling for the=
se companies, as represented by the market caps of the biggest tech compani=
es, is 5-15x higher than it was a decade ago, and should FAAMG keep growing=
, that ceiling may be 5-15x higher in another decade.=C2=A0=C2=A0
As I=E2=80=99ve been thinking about this idea, the house from the Pixar mov=
ie Up keeps coming to mind.=C2=A0
Startups and smaller cap tech companies are the old man=E2=80=99s house, FA=
AMG are the balloons, and Apple breaking the $1 trillion market cap thresho=
ld was the moment the house ripped away from its foundations and took fligh=
t. The balloons and the house keep floating higher, in lockstep. It makes s=
ense for balloons to float, it feels weird for a house to float, but when y=
ou put the two together=E2=80=A6 the physics kinda work.=C2=A0
That said, the averages obscure the specifics, and this is different from c=
ompany to company and vertical to vertical. Some areas that feel expensive =
are actually probably cheap, held back by the psychological barriers of inv=
esting at prices that just feel too high, while other areas might be bubble=
s even if the prices are lower. Some balloons will undoubtedly pop.=C2=A0
Take electric vehicles, a category in which there seems to be a new multi-b=
illion dollar SPAC every day. The category will certainly grow, but the pri=
ces seem wild since they=E2=80=99re tied to the=C2=A0Tesla balloon. Tesla i=
s a great company that may grow into its valuation, but at current multiple=
s, it=E2=80=99s not as solid an anchor as FAAMG. Even if Tesla=E2=80=99s pr=
ice proves to be right, some companies will win and some will lose, as alwa=
ys, but deals are pricing as if they=E2=80=99re all going to win. Nikola co=
ntinuing to trade at an $8 billion market cap seems way out of whack -- bub=
bly.=C2=A0
Or take Gamestop, which was trading on memes, or any number of penny stocks=
 that rocket up 200% in a day. Those are microbubbles, and I=E2=80=99m not =
arguing that they fit into this framework. But bubbles like Nikola, Gamesto=
p, and penny stocks seem to be contained mispricings of the probability of =
success, or downright speculation, as opposed to systemic overvaluation.=C2=
=A0
There=E2=80=99s a very real chance that as FAAMG continues to grow, we don=
=E2=80=99t have a major market correction so much as micro-adjustments of e=
ach company=E2=80=99s probability of reaching the top. We=E2=80=99ll see mo=
re companies that raised at high valuations fail than ever before =E2=80=94=
 money can kill unprepared companies, and a .1% chance is still just a .1% =
chance =E2=80=94 but we=E2=80=99ll also see more companies reach the $100 b=
illion and $1 trillion marks than ever before. Venture returns follow a pow=
er law, and that may become more extreme in the coming years.
Then again, I might look back on this essay with shame in a few years. The =
market could cool off or pop, FAAMG could re-rate to the lower multiples ty=
pically enjoyed by the world=E2=80=99s largest companies, and both public a=
nd private tech company valuations could get slashed. I expect you to call =
me out if that happens.=C2=A0
As for how to apply this? There=E2=80=99s not an easy framework to judge th=
e probability that Company X becomes the next Amazon. This isn=E2=80=99t pr=
ecise. It=E2=80=99s more of a sense check the next time you find yourself t=
hinking,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a bubble=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s competitive out there so people are sacrificing returns to get into th=
e hot deals or buy some growth.=E2=80=9D Maybe there isn=E2=80=99t a trade-=
off between sitting out and being disciplined on price so much as a need fo=
r reframing what being disciplined on price means. The ceiling is higher th=
an ever; it=E2=80=99s dreams all the way up.=20
